    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_710830368" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/710830368" />
    <a title="Ali Nazifpour" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10661959-ali-nazifpour"><img alt="Ali Nazifpour" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1475165172p2/10661959.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/710830368?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ali Nazifpour" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ali Nazifpour" href="/user/show/10661959-ali-nazifpour">Ali Nazifpour</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099451679" href="/book/show/472274.Red_Sorghum">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer710830368" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4071879126073457674"><i>Red Sorghum</i> read to me like a Chinese version of Marquez. By Chinese I mean like those second rate Chinese knock-offs. And I am not a fan of Marquez, I find him overrated. However, if you&apos;re one of the people who has a spontaneous orgasm when they hear the word &quot;Marquez&quot;, you might like this book too. I didn&apos;t.<br/><br/>It&apos;s not like it has no merits at all. The prose reads very beautifully in English, so I guess it must have been even better in Chinese. The imagery and descriptions are very moving. When </span>
  <span id="freeText4071879126073457674" style="display:none"><i>Red Sorghum</i> read to me like a Chinese version of Marquez. By Chinese I mean like those second rate Chinese knock-offs. And I am not a fan of Marquez, I find him overrated. However, if you're one of the people who has a spontaneous orgasm when they hear the word "Marquez", you might like this book too. I didn't.<br /><br />It's not like it has no merits at all. The prose reads very beautifully in English, so I guess it must have been even better in Chinese. The imagery and descriptions are very moving. When it describes the nature and sorghum fields it reads like great poetry. The war and violent scenes are very moving and shocking. But none of these is enough to make it a good novel. And I don't think it is a good novel.<br /><br />Point is, the simple underlying story is simple enough - and not at all artistic. It's a sensational (sentimental), weird, illogical, and extremely nationalistic and nostalgic look upon three generations of Chinese people whose lives are disturbed by war and violence. What is missing though is a convincing plot. What is missing are individual characters who are anything more than generational voice. What is missing is a good novel.<br /><br />I can see why this novel must be attractive to academic readers. It has all the cliches the like. It has this "cultural voice" they love so much, with a touristy and 100% uncritical look on a weird (and inhuman) culture. Matched marriage and forced labor and sexism and other things are presented with a nostalgic love, coated in a "cultural" shell and displayed in an anthropological fashion. Of course the post-colonialists are going to drool over it. And it's narration is non-linear, so post-structuralists are going to drool over it too. It is a novel written for literary snobs the same way cheap romances are written for house wives approaching menopause or pulp fiction written for male teenagers with too much hormone. It's a masturbation book. The reason that it gets more respect is the simple fact that academia is the powerful voice and their preferences and cliches are deemed better than others.<br /><br />But the emperor wears no clothes. As I've said, the plot underneath is very simplistic, with sensationalized love stories and the narrative is completely uncalled for, it's gimmick and nothing more. Rearrange the novel into linear narrative and you have a simple sentimentalized account of the times past.<br /><br />I don't know if Mo Yan's other books are as bad as this one. Maybe they are masterpieces. But this one deserves no Nobel.<br /><br /><b>P.S.</b> You will find more foot fetish in this novel than a Tarantino film. The most laughable part of the novel is the part that a character falls in love with a woman simply because of her foot sticking out of a curtain. And such a small foot! Oh such a small foot! What could a woman do if her foot wasn't small? It was at this point and at such descriptions that I couldn't really take this novel seriously anymore.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4071879126073457674" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

