    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_556635709" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/556635709" />
    <a title="Joshua" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18211332-joshua"><img alt="Joshua" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/556635709?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joshua" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joshua" href="/user/show/18211332-joshua">Joshua</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140168549" href="/book/show/894154.Red_Sorghum">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer556635709" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9142057996034353771">The only thing more ubiquitous in Mo Yan&apos;s prose than the shimmering image of a red field of fluttering sorghum stalks is the repeatedly abrupt appearance of a festering corpse or a newly opened, vigorously gushing flesh wound. Red Sorghum masterfully balances evocative colorful landscapes and morbidly cruel human violence. The contrast is harsh and beautiful and painful.<br/><br/>If you want to understand why Mo Yan was awarded the Nobel a few years ago, read this novel. In my mind, it alone justifies th</span>
  <span id="freeText9142057996034353771" style="display:none">The only thing more ubiquitous in Mo Yan's prose than the shimmering image of a red field of fluttering sorghum stalks is the repeatedly abrupt appearance of a festering corpse or a newly opened, vigorously gushing flesh wound. Red Sorghum masterfully balances evocative colorful landscapes and morbidly cruel human violence. The contrast is harsh and beautiful and painful.<br /><br />If you want to understand why Mo Yan was awarded the Nobel a few years ago, read this novel. In my mind, it alone justifies the award. <br /><br />I've read comparisons of Mo Yan to William Faulkner. To an extent these comparisons hold true for me as well. While Mo Yan's narrative style, in contrast to Faulkner's, is relatively straightforward, both authors have managed to articulate the universal by elaborating upon local circumstances. Red Sorghum takes place in a specific period of Chinese history about which I know next to nothing, nevertheless, the pain and the beauty of Mo Yan's simple human stories ring true to me.<br /><br />This novel will keep you reading and will keep your imagination fully fired throughout. One moment we are in the midst of a raging battle and the next we are riding along side a gang of country bandits engaging in any number of inconceivable villainies. There's something almost Borgesian about the wide ranging scope of Mo Yan's stories.<br /><br />This is a phenomenal book and if you are going to sample Mo Yan start here.<br /><br /><br />Random thought: I've read three novels recently which saw the main character, for varying reasons, hide himself at the bottom of a deep hole in the ground. Red Sorghum, The Silent Cry by Kenzaburo Oe, and The Wind Up Bird Chronicle by Murakami. I'm not sure what the deal is with that... anyway.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9142057996034353771" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


