<div id="review_433229521" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/433229521" />
    <a title="Dorothee Lang" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6043326-dorothee-lang"><img alt="Dorothee Lang" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442475501p2/6043326.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/433229521?book_show_action=true">Oct 13, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dorothee Lang" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dorothee Lang" href="/user/show/6043326-dorothee-lang">Dorothee Lang</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140168549" href="/book/show/894154.Red_Sorghum">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer433229521" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8725378222126597738">&quot;Red Sorghum&quot; is one of the books I once started, but didn&apos;t finish, a book with multiple timelines that reach back to the time when Japan invaded China. The red in the title refers both to the Communist party, and to all the blood that was shed. I was at the Book Fair in Frankfurt when the Nobel Prize for Literature 2012 was announced: Mo Yan. <br/><br/>Reading into it again now, i remembered what i wrote about reading a previous Nobel Winner, Herta Müller: &quot;war, and the hardship it brings on so many lev</span>
  <span id="freeText8725378222126597738" style="display:none">"Red Sorghum" is one of the books I once started, but didn't finish, a book with multiple timelines that reach back to the time when Japan invaded China. The red in the title refers both to the Communist party, and to all the blood that was shed. I was at the Book Fair in Frankfurt when the Nobel Prize for Literature 2012 was announced: Mo Yan. <br /><br />Reading into it again now, i remembered what i wrote about reading a previous Nobel Winner, Herta Müller: "war, and the hardship it brings on so many levels, the way it disrupts families, regions, futures. the approach of the book: history, seen through personal lives." - The same is true for Mo Yan. It's a hard, painful and complex read, spanning 3 generations, detailed in all aspects: rural life in China, and the hardship and cruelties the family has to go through.<br /><br />--<br />PS: this is a part of a longer book review that also includes some impressions from the book fair, and a second author from China: Liao Yiwu, who received one of the most important German book prizes at the book fair, and in counterpart to Mo Yan, had to flee his home country. here's the whole review: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://virtual-notes.blogspot.de/2012/10/words-wars-books-peace-prizes-time.html">http://virtual-notes.blogspot.de/2012...</a> </span>
  <a data-text-id="8725378222126597738" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


