    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_650997362" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/650997362" />
    <a title="Jo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12091097-jo"><img alt="Jo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1346006680p2/12091097.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/650997362?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jo" href="/user/show/12091097-jo">Jo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099451679" href="/book/show/472274.Red_Sorghum">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer650997362" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13530053622756907374">Mo Yan has an amazing way with words and description, this book is so dense with imagery that each page requires careful reading as you struggle to adequately create pictures in your mind from the language. It soon becomes clear why the book is called &apos;Red Sorghum&apos; with reference to it in every chapter and the dark rich soil in which it grows, there is also a consistency in the imagery of the colours red and green tying together the sometimes confusing array of fights and battles that take place</span>
  <span id="freeText13530053622756907374" style="display:none">Mo Yan has an amazing way with words and description, this book is so dense with imagery that each page requires careful reading as you struggle to adequately create pictures in your mind from the language. It soon becomes clear why the book is called 'Red Sorghum' with reference to it in every chapter and the dark rich soil in which it grows, there is also a consistency in the imagery of the colours red and green tying together the sometimes confusing array of fights and battles that take place. Red is the colour not only of the sorghum but of the myriad amount of blood that is spilled throughout the book and that adds rather gruesomely to the richness of the soil; this is not a book to be read by the faint of heart. <br /><br />The book moves around a lot between a span of about fifteen years or so and many times when a new chapter started I was lost as to which time period we were being told about and how that related to the text that came before. The way in which the main characters are referred to by Grandad, Father and Grandma can also be confusing when we know so very little about the narrator but these few points of confusion are my only criticism and could be due to the reader not the writer. <br /><br />When writing about his characters, there are no subtle emotions; they are ruled by love, desire, anger, fear and hatred but then in times of war and in a place where it is a struggle to survive there is no room for ambiguity or siting on a fence. This is an epic tale with Yu Zhan'ao as the epic and flawed hero but it also has an epic cast of secondary characters- it would be hard to call them minor. Uncle Arhat, Pocky Leng, Passion, Black Eye, all play small but pivotal parts, even the animals seem integral to the story but it is the steadfast sorghum and the red sun, the Black water river and the ever shifting light that truly make this such a magical, resonant, timeless story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13530053622756907374" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review650997362">
