<div id="review_1143577385" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1143577385" />
    <a title="Gisela Hafezparast" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24952902-gisela-hafezparast"><img alt="Gisela Hafezparast" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1382532557p2/24952902.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1143577385?book_show_action=true">Dec 27, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gisela Hafezparast" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gisela Hafezparast" href="/user/show/24952902-gisela-hafezparast">Gisela Hafezparast</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140168549" href="/book/show/894154.Red_Sorghum">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24952902-gisela-hafezparast?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24952902-gisela-hafezparast?shelf=i-finally-get-my-turn-bookshelf">i-finally-get-my-turn-bookshelf</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1143577385" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6460635733963938372">I cannot believe I have let this book sit on my bookshelves unread for the past 3 years or so. The reason of course is that from the first few pages it feels very much like a war book, which it is, but it is so much more. It is an epic tale about the Chinese civil war and the Japanese invasion of China and the heroic resistance of the Chinese. I have rarely read a tale so beautiful and sympathetically told which in the main is mostly about murder, slaughter of the innocent and those not so innoc</span>
  <span id="freeText6460635733963938372" style="display:none">I cannot believe I have let this book sit on my bookshelves unread for the past 3 years or so. The reason of course is that from the first few pages it feels very much like a war book, which it is, but it is so much more. It is an epic tale about the Chinese civil war and the Japanese invasion of China and the heroic resistance of the Chinese. I have rarely read a tale so beautiful and sympathetically told which in the main is mostly about murder, slaughter of the innocent and those not so innocent, together with a very complicated love affair. When reading so suffer, love, rejoice and hate with all the characters, but at the end there are really very few of the main characters which when considered can be said to be "good people". Especially the two main characters, one a bandit and war load, the other a strong but very calculating women (although at least she either had to learn to make her own decisions or be sacrificed) I will have to think about for quite a while until I decide where I stand with regard to them. Their son (father) is the only one, although also after a while an accomplished fighter, is the easiest to be sympathised most. It's a tale of old China, although I had to keep telling myself this was the time roughly around the second world war, but I suspect it could have been anytime during China's long history. The cruelty of poor people's life is breathtaking and sometimes feels like you are being dunked into ice-cold water, it is so chilling. And then they get up again, start again - amazing. <br /><br />This book is in line with War and Peace and I will certainly read more of Mo Yan's books. If they are even half as good as this one, he is a very deserving Nobel Prize winner for Literatue.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6460635733963938372" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

