  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2278561664" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2278561664" />
    <a title="TylerGHS2020" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/71701743-tylerghs2020"><img alt="TylerGHS2020" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/images/nophoto/user/c_111x148.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2278561664?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="TylerGHS2020" class="user" itemprop="url" name="TylerGHS2020" href="/user/show/71701743-tylerghs2020">TylerGHS2020</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140168549" href="/book/show/894154.Red_Sorghum">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2278561664" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10248517027499226957">As someone who&apos;s typically interested in war-related books, this didn&apos;t live up to my expectations. It is a fictional history/war book, but still seemed to portray the typical themes of war rather strongly and vividly. I was expecting a more fast-paced read, but this book didn&apos;t follow that style. A lot of the book is related to symbolism. The narrator helps portray the realistic brutalities of war, which seems to be one of the primary themes of the book. The part the plant plays on the novel se</span>
  <span id="freeText10248517027499226957" style="display:none">As someone who's typically interested in war-related books, this didn't live up to my expectations. It is a fictional history/war book, but still seemed to portray the typical themes of war rather strongly and vividly. I was expecting a more fast-paced read, but this book didn't follow that style. A lot of the book is related to symbolism. The narrator helps portray the realistic brutalities of war, which seems to be one of the primary themes of the book. The part the plant plays on the novel seems to be that even through years of war and bloodshed, it still provides food, shelter, etc. There's also some realistic and brutal imagery, which helps convey the themes of this book. Something I found interesting was how the main characters and their opponents aren't fighting for a political party or something of that type, but for their land. And all the struggles the people have are witnessed by the sorghum plants, as they're stained with blood, hence the name "<i>Red</i> Sorghum". This novel is definitely fueled by symbolism rather than suspense or action. I found it rather boring due to that, but it adds a very interesting factor to the book. I gave this book a 3/5 because what it lacks in action and suspense, it compensates somewhat with symbolism and reality. Whether you like this book or not is based completely on personal preference, so if you like fast-paced, suspenseful novels, I wouldn't recommend this. If you like realistic, brutal, symbolic type novels, I would recommend it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10248517027499226957" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


