<div class='bookAuthorProfile__about'>

<span id="freeTextContainer10025438037466622222">Modern Chinese author, in the western world most known for his novel <i>Red Sorghum</i> (which was turned into a movie by the same title). Often described as the Chinese Franz Kafka or Joseph Heller.<br/><br/><i>Mo Yan</i> (莫言) is a pen name and means <i>don&apos;t speak</i>. His real name is Guan Moye (simplified Chinese: 管谟业; traditional Chinese: 管謨業; pinyin: Guǎn Móyè).<br/><br/>He has been awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature 2012 for hi</span>
  <span id="freeText10025438037466622222" style="display:none">Modern Chinese author, in the western world most known for his novel <i>Red Sorghum</i> (which was turned into a movie by the same title). Often described as the Chinese Franz Kafka or Joseph Heller.<br /><br /><i>Mo Yan</i> (莫言) is a pen name and means <i>don't speak</i>. His real name is Guan Moye (simplified Chinese: 管谟业; traditional Chinese: 管謨業; pinyin: Guǎn Móyè).<br /><br />He has been awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature 2012 for his work which "with hallucinatory realism merges folk tales, history and the contemporary". Among the works highlighted by the Nobel judges were <i>Red Sorghum</i> (1987) and <i>Big Breasts &amp; Wide Hips</i> (2004), as well as <i>The Garlic Ballads</i>.<br /><br />Chinese version: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/20094491.__" title="莫言" rel="nofollow noopener">莫言</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="10025438037466622222" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

</div>
